Steps to controlling your pet and keeping it out of trouble:<br>
<br>
1) Use the ‘/guard here’ command where you are camped<br>
<br>
2) Assign an assist (person who is choosing what target to attack), this person should never be used to pull mobs off other people, you should assign a different person for this job. Make a hotkey for /assist &gt;tank&lt;<br>
<br>
3) When using the assist hotkey, first clear your target by hitting &gt;esc&lt;, this insures that the target you chose is the target the assist has targeted. If you don’t and your assist has no one targeted, that target will not change.<br>
<br>
4) The most important thing in controlling your pet is to not get attacked by loose mobs. You do not want your pet defending you.<br>
<br>
5) Find a spot to med behind other casters that aren’t moving around either. This lowers the chance of a mob attacking you first. You are the last person that should get hit in a group.<br>
<br>
6) When your puller yells ‘Incoming’, stand up. Mobs go after people sitting before those who are standing.<br>
<br>
7) The time to send in the pet is sometimes hard to decide. You want to get your pet on the correct target early so that if you are hit, the pet might stay on the right target, but you don’t want him sent into a group of multiple mobs hitting everything in sight (including your pet). I usually wait for most the mobs to be mez’ed or firmly attacking someone else before I send in the pet, but if mobs are moving around you, send in the pet fast so that you can get the pet targeted on something else.<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE EMOTICON START 8) --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/intl/aenglish/images/emoticons/glasses.gif ALT="8)"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END-->  Do not stand near your pet while it’s in battle. If you are attacked and you are in melee range of your pet, he might change targets.<br>
<br>
9) If you get hit, get the mob off you by training it on another member, or just wait for the enchanter to mez it. Once the mob is no longer attacking you back off your pet, and send it back into the correct target. (this is assuming your pet stayed on the correct target while you were hit). This will clear the agro list of your pet.<br>
<br>
10) If your pet gets hit by another mob and your pet remains on the correct target, back off your pet as soon as the other mob is taken care off. This will clear the agro list of your pet.<br>
<br>
11) If re-assist is called, quickly back off your pet, generally tanks are a little slow at re-assisting giving you enough time to back off your pet.<br>
<br>
12) If your pet gets stuck on a mob solo, look for your enchanter to start casting, then mash the ‘/pet back off’ hot key as fast as you can until it’s mez’ed. This will work most the time, but if you suffer from some lag, your enchanter can help you greatly by using stun first. (Talk to your enchanter about this technique.)<br>
<br>
13) If you have a pet run away after a loose mob, you have 2 choices to make:<br>
A) Let it chase the mob and kill it, once you see the experience message, if you don’t see your pet, kill it by going invisible. (there is no harm in the pet fighting the mob, since the mob is going to agro all his friends anyways, but his return trip is dangerous if he uses bad pathing.)<br>
B) Back off your pet immediately and let others kill the mob, and you can use a nuke as well.<br>
<br>
14) When all is lost and your pet is causing problems, go invisible. Do the Earth boot quest and hotkey the boots in a slot in your inventory. It’s the fastest way to kill off your pet.<br>
<br>
Enchanters have a couple of ways to help get a pet off a mob that she/he wants to mez:<br>
<br>
1) Enchanters can use their stun spell to give you an easy opportunity to back off your pet. Their AoE stun spell is rarely resisted and only takes 2 seconds to cast and stun does NOT break mez. Only damage and cancel magic spells break mez.<br>
<br>
2) Enchanter can also wait to mez the mob your pet is on until last, making the job of getting the pet off the mob easier and safer.<br>
<br>
3) Enchanters can also charm the mob that a pet is on to remove from the enemy list and add to the groups offensive power.<br>
<br>
I may have missed a few other tricks, but for the most part, it’s all there. If you follow these guidelines you will have a much better grouping experience.<br>
